-- FACTBOX: Barclays deal structure, investors
-- 
-- Wed Jun 25, 2008 8:42am EDT
-- http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/06/25/us-barclays-investors-idUSL2512816020080625

 

 LONDON  (Reuters) - British bank Barclays ( BARC.L ) raised 4.5 billion pounds ($8.9 billion) from investors including Qatar and Japan's Sumitomo Mitsui ( 8316.T ) to rebuild capital and to fund growth opportunities  

 Under the structure of the deal Barclays will offer its existing shareholders the chance to buy up to 4 billion pounds of shares at a discount, with outside "anchor" investors underwriting the fundraising. Here is the structure of the deal and details on the investors: --to raise 500 million pounds from the sale of 169 million new shares at 296 pence per share to Japan's Sumitomo Mitsui Banking Corp ( 8316.T ). The price is a 4.7 percent discount to Tuesday's closing price. --to raise 4 billion pounds through a placing and open offer of 1.407 billion new shares at 282p per share. The price is a discount of 9.3 percent to Tuesday's closing price. --the open offer shares are available for clawback in full by existing shareholders, who can buy 3 new shares for every 14 owned, up to a maximum of their pro rata entitlement. --the open offer will close on July 17 and new shares will start trading on July 22. --Qatar Investment Authority has agreed to invest up to 1.764 billion pounds for shares in the open offer. QIA was founded by the State of Qatar in 2005 to strengthen its economy by diversifying into new asset classes. The investment is being made through its subsidiary Qatar Holding, the prime vehicle for strategic and direct investments by the State of Qatar. --Challenger has agreed to invest 533 million pounds for shares in the open offer. Challenger is owned by Sheikh Hamad bin Jassim bin Jabr al-Thani, a member of the royal family of Qatar and prime minister, and the chairman of Qatar Holding, and his family. --China Development Bank has agreed to invest up to 136 million pounds in the open offer, including taking up its entitlement for the shares it already owns. CDB, founded in 1994, reports directly to the State Council of China and specializes in financing for construction and development of infrastructure and core industries. --Singapore's Temasek TEM.UL, another existing investor, has agreed to invest up to 200 million pounds in the open offer. The sovereign wealth fund holds and manages a diversified 55 billion pound portfolio and invests in banking and financial services, energy & resources and a broad range of other sectors. --A number of leading institutional shareholders and other investors have agreed to invest up to 1.336 billion as part of the open offer. --The new shares being issued will represent about 19.4 percent of the enlarged share capital. (Compiled by Steve Slater)